"Wales, United Kingdom","of Castell Odwyn,Llanbadarn Odwyn,Cardiganshire,Wales":"Llanbadarn-odwyn, Cardiganshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gruffudd","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Welsh: traditional spelling of   Griffith  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Griffith","meanings":["Welsh (Carmarthenshire and western England): from the Old Welsh personal name <i>Gruffudd</i>, Old Welsh <i>Grip(p)iud</i>, composed of the elements <i>grip</i>, of uncertain significance, + <i>iud</i> ‘chief, lord’."]}]},{"name":"Ieuan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin <i>Iohannes</i>.  See  <b>John</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Iefan","meanings":["Later form of   Ieuan ."]},{"name":"Ifan","meanings":["From Latin <i>Iohannes</i>.  See  <b>John</b>   ."]},{"name":"John","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Ieuan ap Gruffudd was born about 1260, in Llanbadarn-odwyn, Cardiganshire, Wales. He married Ellyw Angharad ferch Maredudd in 1285, in Wales. They were the parents of at least 7 sons. He died in 1359, in Wales, United Kingdom, at the age of 100."},"et":{"about 1260–1359":"umbes 1260–1359","1260–1332":"1260–1332","1285–Male":"1285–Surnud","1287–Male":"1287–Surnud","1290–Male":"1290–Surnud","1298–Male":"1298–Surnud","1300–1392":"1300–1392","1450–1502":"1450–1502","1260–1359":"1260–1359","about 1260":"umbes 1260","ABT    1298":"umbes 1298","ABT    1285":"umbes 1285","1285":"1285","1450":"1450","1392":"1392","1260":"1260","1290":"1290","1359":"1359","1502":"1502","1300":"1300","1332":"1332","1298":"1298","1287":"1287","about 1300":"umbes 1300","ABT    1290":"umbes 1290","about 1287":"umbes 1287","Llanbadarn-odwyn, Cardiganshire, Wales":"Llanbadarn-odwyn, Cardiganshire, Wales","Gwlad Morgan, Wales":